North Korea says they will 'certainly not' unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea’s Minister of Foreign Affairs told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions would exacerbate their mistrust of the United States and that the country would certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons without such qualities.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that in the past year North Korea has taken "significant benevolence measures", such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, breaking down the nuclear testing ground and promising not to increase nuclear weapons and technology.
"We see, however, no corresponding response from the U.S.," he said.
"Without any confidence in the U.S. there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will certainly not unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to the removal of nuclear weapons by which North Korea would be rewarded if it took gradual steps, his words seemed significant in that it did not unilaterally reject the removal of nuclear weapons unconditionally as Pjongang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-Oen and Donald Trump at the very first summit between a president of the U.S. and a North Korean leader on 12 June in Singapore when Kim undertook to work for the "destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea wants a formal end to the Korean War from 1950-53, but the United States said that Pjongang must first give up his nuclear weapons.
Washington also resisted requests to relax strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The U.S. insists on the "destruction of nuclear weapons first" and exerts more pressure by tightening the level of sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive way, and even objecting to the 'declaration of the end of the war," said Ri.
"The perception that sanctions can force us on our knees is a dream of the people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the continuing sanctions make our mistrust worse."
Ri didn't say anything about plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader had brought to the attention of the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister drew attention to three meetings during the past five months between Kim and the South Korean leader Moon Jae-in and added: "If the party were in this matter of nuclear destruction in South Korea and not in the US, the destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end."
The tone of Ri's speech was still dramatically different from last year's, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korea's rockets would be directed to the U.S. Landmass after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "Fire Arrowman" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened to "completely destroy North Korea," commended Kim for his courage because he had taken steps to disarm, but he said that much work still needs to be done and that sanctions should remain there until North Korea destroys nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said that he didn't have a time frame for this, and said, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pjonyang for the steps they have taken.
But, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo, Thursday told the UN Security Council that: "Application of sanctions by the Security Council must continue zealously and without letup until we realize the complete, final, confirmed destruction of nuclear weapons."
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously intensified sanctions against North Korea in an effort to fund Pjongång's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
