Harvard students are taking a course on enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year allows all his pre-graduate students to get more sleep in an effort to counteract the growing macho culture of studying by coffee-driven 'all-day sessions'.
An academic found that students at the world's top university are often ignorant when it comes to the basic principles of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleeping medicine at the Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believed was the first of his kind in the U.S.A.
He was inspired to start the course after he had given a talk about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
'At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why do they tell me this first, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had yet told her how important sleep is--which surprised me,' he said to The Telegraph.
The course, first offered that year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their general well - being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at the Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The hour course involves some interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a dormitory, where students on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books need to click to be told about the effect of coffee and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep time routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
'We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know--just as you have the right to know the health impact of choosing to smoke cigarettes,' added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride in 'learning' still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
To make sure you get enough sleep of good quality, a student's 'secret weapon' should be to avoid stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said--even to avoid gaining weight, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course after he took one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to pursue a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with each other.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effect of 'blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which may disturb your circadian rhythm and may cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
