And now a page from our "Sunday Morning" calendar: September 30, 1882, today 136 years ago, and WE REALLY FURTHER ... the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device called the Geiger counter.
Since then, the Geigerteller has been a pillar of science, and it has also become a pillar of pop culture, as in the 1950 movie "Bells of Coronado," in which those two unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans played:
Man: "What on earth is this?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put on these headsets, you can even hear the effects of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.
Evans, "Oh, my God, it's about to crack!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
