The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common and soprano bat as well as the brown long-eared and daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardene in Western Ross.
Special recorders will be placed on the property at important locations to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile recordings using hand indicators.
Expert clan channels of all recordings will check the frequency of the bat calls and determine which species do.
A habitat map and report will then be compiled to create a detailed landscape-scale view of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation consultant for NTS hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management such as pasturage and how to best manage forest lands for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined significantly during the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleep and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose risks, as well as fly paper and some chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo orientation technique to point out bugs and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres [76,000 ha] of land throughout the country, is very serious about bats.
It has ten trained experts who regularly carry out surveys and bedside inspections and sometimes perform rescues.
The organization even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threeave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal site for them.
"Here at Threave we have a wonderful area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many veteran trees and all the good habitat.
But there is so much about bats that are still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us to understand better what they need to thrive."
He emphasizes the need to seek for bats before conservation in properties is done because it is possible that unknowing destruction of a single birthplace can mean 400 females and young children's death and annihilate an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb, or prevent them or destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to jump in to help.
